I recently moved from exclusively doing underwater photography to taking pictures on land which moved me into the Nikon D850.  This course was extremely helpful to learn the menu and camera features way faster than the typical "hunt and peck" method.  Very easy to follow and easy to understand.  Michael is great with explanations and adding just enough detail to explain the "why" behind a lot of the settings even when it's not one most will ever use.  The course overall is well worth the cost and doesn't take long to complete.  Sitting in a live course for this content would be mind numbing as each person learns at a different pace, putting this course in the on-demand space is the best option allowing you to pause the video to practice or follow along with the menu changes.  Some of the settings we won't ever use but it's good to understand how they work and what they are for.  The only part I would have liked to see is the inclusion of when a particular feature would be unavailable in the menu.  Like what other settings affect when you can or cannot make a change.  Since the camera simply tells you that a setting is "not available in the current configuration", I've found it hard to figure out which setting affects which features.  Example, there are times when you can't enable the HDR photo feature (fyi, I still don't know which setting is causing this to be unavailable ;).)  Overall great course and great teacher.

content: Wording of some of the questions is confusing.

Thanks for putting this course online for free.
However, here are some points to consider if ever wanting people to pay for any of the courses.
1. The course is just basically power point slides. No video. Just photos and voiceover with directions.
2. The directions and preparation process is unclear.I did not understand a thing of what I'm supposed to do. I'm from the Middle East, and I still didn't understand.
3. If the course is in English language, then please make sure the words are translated correctly (example; Loumy is Dry Lime, not Lemon)
4. If the course is in English language, then please make sure the words are pronounced correctly and the spelling is correct (there were numerous mistakes)
5. It's important to clarify what the ingredients are named outside of the Middle East. You say yoghurt and jameed (yoghurt) and zabadi, and they're all a bit different. If the course is in English, it's most probably for people living for example in Europe, who can't find Jameed
6. again clarify what the ingredients are, example Meat. What kind of meat? beef? lamb? chicken? and what piece from the animal is it?
7. Avoid saying unnecessary things. Example; "Plastic" plate. It's just a plate or a bowl.
8. The course is titled as a recipe, and there's more about the country and culture. It's better to either put in something small about the country, or make a separate course about the culture

content: Till now i have received several feedbacks related to ielts speaking. However, this is the first time that i'm able to understand with great depth about the knowledge that is being provided. Hopefully it would be beneficial for others as well.

Simon's course is the best. It explores all activities of Speaking part.
The advice and tips, gives me more confidence and certainly helps to improve my English.

Finally I have some time to update my feedback (after finishing the course)! It was a pretty busy time (you know, the end of the year…), so the format of the course (short lessons) turned out extremely handy. Even if I had no free time, I tried at least watching a couple of videos during lunch or before going to sleep.

Previously I would say “I like this course” but now I can say “I’m a huge fan of it”. You see, it’s vocabulary! :D Materials contain a lot of new (for me) phrases and words, and even idioms. Hope I can remember them and use them during the exam.

Also I found several useful tips related to the IELTS speaking test in general. I mean not only about answers and questions, but what to expect and how to behave. I even think I can use some of them on a job interview (not only on the exam).

At the end of the day (I try to use new phrases even here :), I love this course and would recommend it for those who are preparing for the IELTS. But do not forget to practice!

Thank you Simon for this programme, and good luck all of the students! Let’s get the maximum band score!

The way these 11 chapters are designed, really encapsulates the essence of Sanskrit.  It is definitely a good initiative you have taken to increase the  awareness and interest in this rich language.

This is a technically superb course that sticks to its title 'Sanskrit Parichay' (i.e. Introduction to Sanskrit).
